But at the same time they’re supposed to be revealing the actual doll on the child’s play website today so what was the point of not showing it on the teaser? But i would like for the people that automatically hate this just because you’re mad Dõn and brad aren’t apart of it. They chose not to do it and stick with their own brand so the other creator of child’s play went a different route and now we get to have child’s play back in the theater which y’all should be happy about! The cult of chucky was horrendous we need to be scared again and not laughing at chucky. text: I do not care for this change in the storyline for Chucky because a malfunctioning animatronic doll would just make it's gears rapidly move and make the doll look like it's having a seizure and repeat or sound insane when playing the programmed sentences it has in its system, this isn't a malfunctioning doll, this is a doll with an agenda to kill so why would it do that unless it was programmed to do so? Because like a Terminator... Terminators are programmed to kill, they can't get to that point through nothingness so who programmed this doll to kill? That's why I don't like this change to the storyline, because by doing it this way it makes the story multifaceted that they have to stop the doll and they also have to stop the programmer. I prefer the magic from the first movie even though for today's standards it might be considered cheesy, in a weird way it still makes more sense than a doll which imprints on Andy and then becomes a killer.

text: As a HUGE fan of the Child's Play franchise, My thoughts on this new movie are honestly mixed. I'm excited for this. BUT.....I'm still trying my hardest to be skeptical about this reboot cause Child's Play was one of the 1st horror movies I've ever seen and it's the 1st classic (by classic I mean old school) horror movie I've watched and it's one of the few horror movies that got me into the horror genre and why I love horror movies today, so I want this remake to be made and treated with care even though Don Mancini and the other casts aren't gonna be apart of it and even though I'm a HUGE fan of the series, I'm being completely honest when I say not all of the movies are great. Here are my thoughts on the movies  Child's Play - A Classic  Child's Play 2 - A fun time Child's Play 3 - Watchable but can be mediocre Bride of Chucky - A very fun guilty pleasure  Seed of Chucky - Not Good Curse of Chucky - A sequel that respects the franchise Cult of Chucky - A very deep and thoughtful sequel  So I honestly like all of the Chucky movies except for Child's Play 3 and Seed of Chucky. Child's Play 3 is okay and is self aware of what it is, but Seed of Chucky is by far the worst movie in the franchise.  As a person who loves this franchise, I WILL be seeing this movie and I want it to be a success. Btw the producers of "IT" are making this, so it can't be terrible, but I will be counting days until the time of waiting is up and the watch and judgement shall be revealed.

text: I fought 15 guys at once. Fully armed to the teeth. Ak-47s and Grenades. One had a rocket launcher. All I had was my bare hands tied behind my back on to a chair. I flipped back and broke the chair. One guy lunged his rifle barrel at my stomach but I caught it and twisted it just in time for him to pull the trigger and shoot the ceiling. I flung the gun hard to hit his face with the stock. The second guy came at me with a knife. I quickly twisted his hand and took control by getting around him with the knife at his neck. The other 13 were in front of me. Holding their fire. I shoved him into 3 of them. Shifted right and flipped another to the ground. Slid onto the floor to scoop another guys legs. I quickly crawled behind the counter as the other 8 fired lead into it. I was able to get a hold of another knife. Thank god. I flung it at one from around the corner of the counter. As the 7th tried to slide over the counter. I kicked him in the nuts. Picked him up with his gun to his head. 6 guys right in front of me. I did it again. Pushed the enemy into another 2 guys. Leaving 2 on the left and two on the right. Before the ones on the right could react I grabed one and twisted his wrist extended his arm shoving my hand in his face. Quickly broke his elbow out of place and flipped him. Kicked the other guy in the balls and knocked him out with a quick powerful punch. The other two stood there in shock on the other side of the bodies. Dropped their guns and put their hands up. I ran at them and dropped kicked them both in the face. I left the door after throwing two Grenades in there with them. As I walked away from the explosion behind me I said...   “OH YEAH YEAH”

text: I wonder how they're going to make Chucky relevant in the modern day. He was a parody of a very specific toy fad in the 80s. Toys in general are less relevant these days, and the whole talking doll thing is way past long dead. I feel like you'd have to completely readapt the core concept of a killer toy, only having it inspired by the original movie.   But Chucky still looks like Chucky in this movie, so it seems like they're just trying to twist it into something different. It should be more distinguished as its own thing. It'll only piss off people who are fans of the original for changing it, as apposed to standing as its own movie.

text: The doll is going to be an AI doll which to me is more realistic than a voodoo doll and I know all you die hard fans may be disappointed but to me personally do the fact that we have so many things in our homes linked to our lives (alexa, siri, google home, etc...) makes it more scary than voodoo. Its a remake but its supposed to be different. this is a TEASER, of course they aren't going to show the doll. The whole idea of remakes is the bring in new audiences to spread the child's play legacy, but also makes us question all the things we have in your homes and phones that have basically all our information. I think this is a better spin for this day and age. don mancini (the creator of child's play) originally didn't even want voodoo in the movie  it was all supposed to be andy initially but the studio changed it. Anyways I am excited and I think this movie is going to definitely be dark and scare a new generation  in a way that questions our own choices as consumers...

text: 1) Even if this movie turns bad, Don Mancini's "Prime Timeline" of Chucky movies is still going so it won't be affected nor this is "The New Version from Now On". MGM has the rights to the first movie, this is why they can make this happen, but they won't reboot the franchise as a whole. Unless this movie is a hit and can spawn new sequels, but in its own universe.  2) This is a solid trailer and it actually makes me interested in checking it out. Will it have an army of Chuckies?  3) These are the only things I ask for: a script that is mostly consistent/makes sense with characters I can get behind (the original movies have cheesy moments, they're not flawless, but come on, at least be on their level please), and I absolutely want animatronic effects for the dolls. Do that, and I'll watch it. As a Chucky fan this is also the only occasion I have to see a Chucky film on the big screen, so I partially hope it's solid so I can have a fun time at the theater.

text: I'm a fan of Chucky and the first Child's Play movie is one of my favorites to this day having grown up in the 90's. Upon hearing about this reboot or remake I was a little bit skeptical about the whole AI robot Chucky. But understanding why the production company chose to go this route makes sense and just thinking about it makes perfect sense in todays standards. If the company followed the same suite as the original movie, then there's really no need for a reboot. They did the same thing with "IT" and I'm pretty sure some people weren't on board with the new Pennywise because they didn't think that no one could top Tim Curry, but Bill Skarsgård killed it. So the same goes with this movie and we also get the producers of "IT" as well. I'm on board and I can't wait and as for the people who's saying that we didn't get to see Chuckys face or hear him talk...just think about the first Venom trailer that we got, we didn't get anything in that first trailer either.

text: My two cents; "Child's Play" needed a new direction / clean slate as the "possessed sentient doll" was out of mileage (and I LOVE Chucky and Dourif's performance). I found it a bit offputting how they created "new" historical nemeses for Chucky who were never referenced in the earlier movies (sure, sure, hindsight is 20/20 'n all...) I personally found the last film "Cult" to be incoherent and boring (the idea of one soul inhabiting myriad hosts didn't "jibe" with me, plus the presence of Tiffany in human form seemed to both retcon and yet confirm that "Bride" and "Seed" happened..?)  Anyhoo, I'm guessing this new iteration is going for an "A.I. Malfunction" angle and that's potentially cool too, even if Chucky is no longer a sentient "human". Plus, as another commenter said, what kid wants a cabbage patch doll with 3 stock phrases in the days of wi-fi and A.I. and internet and iDevices?

text: Everyone is complaining about Chucky being AI instead of him being possessed by a serial killer, but i feel like it’s more frightening that Chucky is an AI. Think about it, Chucky, in this movie, is a doll that kills with absolutely no remorse, no emotion, and no speaking. The fact that he’s silent makes it scarier. People in this film won’t know Chucky’s next move, they won’t know where he is, and don’t know what he wants - because he’s a doll with no emotion, no brain, and no ability to speak his mind (since he doesn’t have one).

text: No Brad voicing Chucky? No longer a possessed doll, but a robot?    Damn, that's sad. I have a feeling I'm gonna like the TV series being made by the original makers much more than this movie, which is made by others.  Chucky is supposed to be a freaking creep, with a lot of comical murder to it.   This will just purely be scary. Chucky is supposed to make you laugh too! Kind of like Tim Curry's IT was funny.   The original IT in my opinion was much better. The new one felt rushed...  The fat kid and the black kid barely seemed to be much of big characters, but in the original, the character development of each kid was amazing!   I'm not one of those people that always things the original is better than the remake...  But it often is.   I can admit that the Halloween movie that came out about a decade or so ago,  that showed Michael as a kid too, was AN AMAZING remake. Hands down better than the original, although the original is truly classic and fun to watch.

Oh yeah... it became all about torture porn and cheap jump scares as opposed to nail biting suspense, haunting imagery and memorable characters. text: Ok, for those of you who are confused about this, Orion Pictures maintains the rights to the ORIGINAL Child's Play. Therefore, this reboot takes it in a different direction (no Don Mancini, no Brad Dourif or Charles Lee Ray, no voodoo). Don Mancini has been still developing sequels to his original film with the latest being Cult of Chucky. THIS film is in no way connected to that, as is obvious with the "reboot" nature of it and the drastic changes to the source material. This film will poise Chucky as an A.I. gone awry. Most people hate this idea as it bears similarities to "Terminator" and "I, Robot". Obviously someone greenlit this thing so we'll see how it pans out this summer. Like I said it's based on a rights issue and perhaps the only reason this film got made was to capitalize on the character before the rights to the first film went to Don himself.

text: I live for Chucky!!! ♡ I love creepy dolls and eerie movies. The original Child's Play always creeped me out. I love it to this day! I just watched it a few weeks ago even lol The 2nd and 3rd were ok, after that it just got worse and worse. It's a miracle if I even watch any of the generic sequels they make anymore. I've seen almost all of the films, but only once for most of the sequels. So I wouldn't even know how many there are. I tried to watch the newest one and didn't even finish it. 😂 I did watch Bride of Chucky, and Seed of Chucky, back when they came out. I've only seen Seed once or twice. And Bride several times. They're ok for a random movie to watch, they're not horrible for their genre. Although I'm not a big fan of horror comedy unless it's well done. But they're alright. It's been so long since I watched Seed, that I don't remember it. But I'm excited for this. I actually am very happy that they are making so many horror remakes. I enjoy it. Now, do I still think the originals are best? Well duh. And do I still want good, new horror movies made? Of course! I don't watch remakes and compare them to originals. I don't expect them to be the same. Or always have the same iconic scenes, quotes, or anything else. It's nice when they have those things, but I don't need them. Because I don't want to think of it as the same thing. I like to watch it as a new thing. It's own story, just inspired by another. That helps me enjoy it more, and not be so letdown. If I expect a movie to be identical to the original, I'm going to be extremely disappointed. So I don't see it that way. Instead, I see it as a way to bring the oroginal movie back into the spotlight. For everyone. Especially younger people who might not have seen it. And it's exciting too. It kind of brings back all those nostalgic feels for us who grew up with it. I love it! And it's something to get curious about if we've seen the original.  We might love the originals and hold high standards for remakes. But at the end of the day, if you don't like the remake, it doesn't mean anything for the original. The original will still be here, and still be enjoyed by the same amount of people, and probably even more so after the remake.

text: Finlandia: Los medios de comunicación cubren la noticia del Foro del Parlamento sobre la sustracción forzada de órganos  ) Un foro sobre la sustracción forzada de órganos llamó la atención de los medios de comunicación más prominentes de Finlandia. Los periódicos más importantes del país, Helsingin Sanomat, Metro, Aamulehti, Lapin Kansa y 11 medios de comunicación de Internet publicaron noticias sobre el foro que se celebró en el Parlamento finlandés en Helsinki el 13 de noviembre.   El foro fue organizado por la diputada Eva Biaudet. Varios invitados pronunciaron discursos, entre ellos Ethan Gutmann, periodista y escritor que ha investigado la sustracción de órganos, Heikki Mäkisalo, experto en trasplantes de órganos del Hospital Central de la Universidad de Helsinki, y Marja Heinonen-Guzejevilta, experta en ética médica.    Marja Heinonen-Guzejev dijo a los asistentes al foro que un artículo publicado en The American Journal of Transplantation en 2016 mostró que el 63% de los órganos suministrados a las cirugías de trasplante en el mundo provenían de China. Dijo que muchos países han aprobado leyes que prohíben a sus ciudadanos obtener trasplantes de órganos en China, incluyendo Taiwán, Israel, España, Italia y Noruega. También sugirió que se utilicen técnicas de ADN para recopilar más pruebas.    Heinonen-Guzejev también mencionó la recién fundada Coalición Internacional para Acabar con el Abuso de Trasplantes, un tribunal independiente que tiene como objetivo investigar a organizaciones gubernamentales e individuos involucrados en la sustracción forzada de órganos en China.    Varios periódicos y medios de comunicación de Internet publicaron el artículo "El trasplante de órganos en China solo requiere unas pocas horas: La mayoría de los órganos provienen de prisioneros de conciencia". El artículo señala que la mayoría de las víctimas de este crimen son practicantes de Falun Dafa.    Helsingin Sanomat dijo a los lectores que en China los prisioneros de conciencia son sometidos con frecuencia a pruebas de sangre y ADN. Si un paciente necesita unos órganos, los hospitales del gobierno pueden organizar la cirugía en pocas horas.    "China realiza más de 100.000 cirugías de trasplante de órganos cada año. La verdad es que se trata de una violación de los derechos humanos y una matanza a gran escala", afirma el artículo.   El artículo también presentó a Falun Dafa, como una práctica de mejoramiento personal que beneficia el cuerpo y la mente. El artículo decía que antes de que el partido comunista chino lanzara la persecución en julio de 1999, más de 70 millones de personas en China practicaban Falun Dafa. El número de cirugías de trasplante de órganos en China ha aumentado exponencialmente desde que comenzó la persecución.

text: I'm both hyped and a little worried. I mean, I've always loved the Child's Play Series (except Seed of Chucky, that was so terrible, fuck that noise), even the ones that went straight to Netflix were actually really good. I mean on one hand, I kind of want to see how they bring Chucky into the modern era of toys (the scanner was a dope touch), but at the same time I'm kind of pissed that Hollywood won't just leave well enough alone. I've always dug the supernatural element child's play had going for it, and I hope maybe they'll bring that over to this reboot, but I'm also mad that they're even making a reboot in the first place.   Sorry if you don't agree with me, feel free to argue my point, maybe I'm just a sucker for the classics who isn't a real fan of change.

text: Hate to be that guy, but getting your probably 10 year old son a doll, even if it's wickedly high tech, would not be a good thing socially. For starters, I can't imagine the amount of bullying he'd go through if other kids from his school at his age or older knew. Wedgies, locker stuffings, swirlies and all the verbal putdowns a kid like him would get, all because his mom bought him a high-end doll.  Also, I'd bet the kid would grow up weird if that doll is supposed to make-up for a lack of friends.  Aside from how the kid would be, this trailer seems like a "meh" to me. So the doll is high-tech, with facial scanners and robot shit. Is it still possessed, or are we getting a pint-sized Terminator?

text: Guys, although there wasn't a lot of Chucky in this first Child's Play reboot trailer, you can actually hear him in the final moments of the trailer! Around 0:54, if you listen very closely and turn up the volume really loud, Chucky can be heard saying, "Andy" in a really high-pitched whisper. The reason why he is high-pitched is only because, since the robot is not Charles Lee Ray, a grown man in a child's toy's body, the reboot Chucky is intended to be a child's toy and have a child's voice. Unfortunately, for us Chucky fans, we're probably gonna hear a baby, techno Chucky.

text: Yeah, this is probably gonna suck. It looks like Chucky’s a robot now instead of a voodoo cursed doll or whatever you wanna call it. Also, I really think that they’re abandoning the wise cracking Chucky and sticking with a scarier and more serious Chucky. Maybe he doesn’t even talk much. The way he kills people is obviously looking way more elaborate which I’m kinda iffy on. On the one hand, that noose machine Andy’s mom was hooked up to looked pretty cool, but, on the other hand, that’s just not who Chucky is. He’s a slasher, not a Saw wannabe. He supposed to be somewhat smart or, at the very least, not just a stupid killing machine, not a goddamn engineer. This looks like he has no motive as well. I may be wrong about that, but it looks like Chucky is gonna be an unaware killing machine/an AI with no personality. He seems more like the new Michael Myers more than the original Chucky, which kind of bums me out. I really hope that they prove me wrong.

text: For a moment, I thought I was watching a trailer for *Saw* because at 0:53 , it has the _look & feel_ that the *Saw* movies have!  This _Child's Play_ is certainly going to be interesting to say the least because your going to have the _old generation_ and the _new generation_ probably clashing over whether this is going to be good and/or bad because people who grew up with  *Chucky*  know what made  *Chucky*  ,  _Chucky_  and that is his *voice* ! One other important factor was what made the original child's play so important to begin with to create this long legacy thus far and that was the use of  *VooDoo*  ! Having a criminal cast his soul over into the next object before he died was a genius idea for a way to keep this killer alive so he could continue his petty criminal life! 🔫  There's only _one_ thing that's either going to *make this movie good or make this movie bad* and that's going to be the _voice_ . Nothing else matters. The voice is simply going to make it or break it! ❗  🚫  #NotMyChucky   🚫

Scared me a little with the first and second movie, but I grew used to it all and just enjoyed this guy. (His wife as well. Also the kid. Can't forget those two, must not leave them out of the spotlight in this comment.)  So whenever I hear anything or anyone mentioning Chucky, I immediately stop everything I'm doing and get into whatever it is. I did the same to see this trailer and definitely will once it comes out. Love you Chucky, Andy, Tiffany and Glen/Glenda! 💖 ~I'm sorry for the long comment.

text: Unpopular Opinion: I'm actually looking forward to this. I am a huge fan of the original Child's Play, it terrified me as a child, but once I was 14 I was able to watch the films and not be scared, and genuinely enjoy them. I enjoyed the first three, Bride, and even Curse. That being said however, I felt that the original series has gone off the rails with Cult of Chucky. I felt Cult of Chucky was an absolute nightmare, it made Andy into a complete moron, there were countless loose ends, and it felt more like a parody than an actual installment. In other words, I think Child's Play actually NEEDS a proper reboot. The series just feels like something that needs to die off because its no longer scary. But because Chucky is so popular, we don't want to see him totally die but at the same time we're sick the same thing over and over again.  So yea if anything I find this new concept refreshing as hell and am looking forward to it

text: I was explaining to my friends on Twitter that Brad Dourif could not just only be the patron of the reboot but will do an uncredited role as the voice of Chucky in a sinister turn in the reboot. Brad is known to do these roles as surprise appearances, especially in Ready Player One and a Calvin Harris Video to name a few. Brad Dourif had been an Acting Teacher in colleges and universities for thousands of Actors and Actresses since early 80's, he brings out the best in the cast and crew of movie makers, he even taught the Teenage Don Mancini in college. Brad was in Lord of the Rings and picked Billy Boyd to be as Glen Glenda, another lord of the rings star is Liv Tyler who was picked as Karen who turned it down and is replaced by Aubery Plaza. So, having saying that, Brad may be a quiet guy in real life however he knows who is good at acting in this or that, he is knowledgeable that way. Even Fiona like her father is not doing the "Not my Chucky" rant and she is starring in the TV Series so she is supporting her Father. The problem with Don Mancini, Jennifer Tilly, Alex Vincent, Christine Elise is they feel they won't get paid enough, but I don't see why they are paranoid because the reboot is going to boost the ratings as revival, and they need the help since Curse of Chucky is 5 million audience subtotal and Cult is down to 2 million audience subtotal. Brad is the Star, let's be honest, Brad is what people want in Child's Play, I think there is some tension and jealously towards Brad since he is the best actor in the world, and for a guy who quoted "I am a whore when it comes to money" to not be concerned along with his Daughter is astonishing to me, but I am not surprised about Brad's influence and knowledge of picking a cast that movie makers trust enough to make him do so. Chucky's voice in the Reboot/remake is STILL a massive mystery, still nobody knows who it is? My opinion that it is Bradders himself. This is brilliant marketing.

text: 1. Kid looks too old to be playing with a preschool level toy. The T-1000 worked as an adult, humanoid cyborg, but as a killer toy, the premise isn't scary, and kind of gets ridiculous in light of the fact that Chucky is two foot tall and all Andy would have to do is to get Chucky wet. Siri stops talking when you dunk your I phone in water. Annable also explored the blood ritual that Don Mancini originally wanted to use as the mechanism for bringing Chucky to life. So I remain totally unimpressed with this.  As it's own thing, without invoking the fandom from an already established IP that is still releasing projects,  it might actually be good, but as a  Chucky movie, I have a feeling this is going to be worse than Seed of Chucky and Child's Play 3

text: I might be in the minority here but so far I think this looks great. The viral marketing campaign with the Kaslan Corporation has been really awesome and I think this was a fantastic first look. Fingers crossed that in the next trailer Chucky's reveal resonates with both new and old fans of the original and we finally get to hear his iconic laugh! Though I understand the reboot/remake fatigue in Hollywood now and days 'IT' was an amazing retelling (should I dare say better than the original? > .<) and this is being produced by the same people.  I always say, the originals aren't going anywhere and are always gonna be there if they somehow mess it up. Not to mention the original franchise is still continuing their story so us fans are kinda getting the best of both worlds/universes. I've lost count on how many times I've watched this, lol; couldn't help myself and made a mash-up trailer with Toy Story. Even as a kid I always thought that though very different, they kind of share the same concept. If anyone wants a quick laugh it's on my channel. Only thing i'm a little worried about is the voice but I have hope. So far we've gotten Halloween, 'IT', and are about to get Pet Semetary in 2 months! So pls Hollywood, if you're going to continue remaking these cherished horror/slasher franchises GIVE US A NEW NIGHTMARE ON ELM STREET! Freddy holds a special place in my heart as i'm sure he does to millions of others and I know if given the right treatment our favorite glove wielding dream demon slasher can be resurrected for the new generation. Also, last thing - Aubrey Plaza as Andy's mom? I feel like an old fart lol but I have a feeling she's going to be amazing.  #FriendsTillTheEnd
author: ScreenLight

text: Gabriel Bateman is a good actor. In Benji, he was outstanding but he is too old to play Andy. I would like to have seen more details surrounding The Strangler, Charles Lee Ray. Just think of a movie where you're led to believe it's another movie about another serial killer only to have a crazy twist around the middle where he transfers his spirit into a doll and befriends a boy named Andy. Kind of like From Dusk Until Dawn but instead of a crime spree ending with vampires you get a serial killer slasher/mystery culminating in transference of spirits and betrayal. Said movie with the name, The Strangler, would be nice.

text: My opinion on those that are commenting about Hollywood rebooting and not being creative... I think what's happening is that streaming like Netflix and whatnot are coming out with their own shows and more and more people are more in tuned to that. They're small series you don't have to pay attention to it and for very long. Which is the issue that we have nowadays are no one can really focus on something for very long. When it comes to Hollywood movies it seems you can't make too many varieties of movies anymore because not everyone wants to sit there for an hour and a half to two hours possibly two and a half hours on one thing because the attention span isn't there anymore. As you can notice even the theaters have less eating now that most theaters are getting recliners. I remember going to the theaters 10 years ago or more and all seats are almost always full and those were before recliners. Now the only time a reclining seat Theatre gets full is it big movie during opening weekend or at least the first week. It's a generational thing I think. But again this is just an opinion there's no fact behind this. Just something I've noticed
author: Aline Gosselin

text: Yo chief im gonna be real, i loved childs play as a kid, i loved it all the way up until about childs play 4. I mean personally i just thought childs play 3 was a bit boring but i think thats just because i dont remember much of it but i still loved it, just a bit boring to me. Anyways anymore it feels like they are ruining the franchise. I understand that maybe the constant recreation just isnt for me and perhaps others may like it but at the same time i think maybe we should just leave it alone at some point? The last chucky was honestly just hollywood taking a shit on the entire thing. It was so bad that i can barely remember what even happened in that movie. All i remember is that there were so many chuckys and the plot was just all over the place. It made no sense. It isnt like they were going for a non linear plot either, if they were it would have it would have been much more organized however all we got was a bunch of low budget good guy dolls running around. I don't mean to shit on someone elses work but im afraid this series is just getting strung out just to make a little cash. I think the original first few did an amazing job at showing the killer doll's life and it gave the viewers all the information they needed on him while still leaving them on the edge of their seats wanting more. They expanded the universe, introduced new characters, kept the og main character as the main character for the most part until they got up to seed of chucky but even then that movie expanded the universe and provided us with some good content and more insight on chucky. Maybe im doing too much i tend to talk a lot? Idk. Anyone else kinda agree? Id love to discuss more

Chucky was my childhood nightmare and this movie excites me.

text: From the looks of the trailer, it doesn't look half-bad and as a fan of practical effects, i'm glad they are making a comeback and using practical for chucky And all.  I didn't hate this teaser. Which is quite a shocker. I liked it. Yes. It is another horror remake, but I really liked the fact that this teaser really did not give that much away.  I liked the song choice and how it was edited, the kid looks like he is pretty decent, Aubrey Plaza in a role like this is intriguing, the lighting in the trailer was nice. I loved the use of reds and blues. And overall the idea behind it I don't mind. It's like Child's Play meets Small Soldiers. And it most definitely looks like it will be a hard R. I liked seeing the bits of practical effects.  It is not any worse or as insulting as Don Mancini's last 4 sequels as i felt 3 was the last Child's Play movie for me. So yeah, it looked interesting to me. I was curious about it anyway. So this teaser definitely helped pique my interest. I am still very leery of it but I am going to give it a chance.. This looks something different than the overused Voodoo thing which has been done to death, the AI thing feels fresh just like Small Soldiers or that Funzo episode of Simpsons

text: I know people are peeved about the changes, but I do think the *supernatural* killer doll has become rather outdated, the addition of AI though adds potential for commentary in how we let technology raise our children and an extra layer of unpredictability.   We could also have a different dynamic to the kid in the original. Maybe instead of trying to switch bodies, the Chucky in this movie might be an over obsessive AI, killing anyone who stands in the way between him from the kid. Or maybe its about the dangers of refusing to grow up, how childhood can consume and destroy any future you had. I mean the kid look's like he's a bit old to be playing with a doll, ain't he? There's a lot of different ways to go in the realms of Science Fiction, I hope this at least explores it.

text: In all fairness, lets be honest, we're in 2019, so many things have been invented and ideas used, especially in movies, how many more originals ideas do you think there are? Even if it was "original" somebody would complain that its similar to something else.  In all honesty these are inevitable and i personally prefer to have it be our favorite characters than someone nobody cares about, its not going to be the same, but things could always be worse, its hard to keep anybody happy, especially everyone, nobody is ever satisfied for the most part lol, especially if you're critiquing everything and comparing it to the originals, people dont live forever so our heroes, villains and icons will change over time, things never stay the same, me personally, id rather enjoy something than be disappointed so i dont compare things cause then you're setting yourself up for your own disappointment, you have to treat everything as its own thing cause even if its a part of the same story or series, chances are not everyone involved the first time will be there every single time to follow after.  Yeah im more excited and interested about the show cause its brad dourif and following some characters we know, and new ones, but if you think about it, chucky in fact was a robotic toy back then though not as advanced at the time, only difference is, this one is more advanced and is technically possibly self aware and or malfunctioned or purposefully was altered, who knows, and back then it was a lower quality robot doll but with charles lee ray's soul put inside of it, chucky was high end back then, nobody thought of him as a robot cause he had a soul but the regular dolls responded when talked too and had phrases and such, a regular toy put together could not do that, it had to have some sort of intelligence or chip involved which yes does equal robot, it wasnt just toy parts alone, just my opinion though, the only real difference is just not having a soul this time in terms of chucky himself

text: Okay I'm not happy with this remake yeah yeah complain all u want but this doesn't feel right I know it's all new and improved but what made Chucky so scary in the original was that he didn't have any technology or anything special he was just a cute little innocent doll and he was actually alive and killer which scared people and watch the very first child's play movie trailer and compare to this their so different and if their was only 1 2 or even 3 chucky movies it would be fine to remake but nope theirs 7 and if u haven't seen the latest from last year cult of chucky I'm not gonna spoil it for u but they ended it with a cliffhanger begging for a sequel honestly and their gonna remake it? And well chucky being posessed by Charles Lee Ray was what made him scary cause he acted human he could bleed grow fingernails have sex and many more and chucky isn't posessed in the new 1 he's just a mindless robot and I will admit this is a pretty good and scary plot a animatronic being hacked and killing. But not for chucky cause people know him as a human stuck inside of a doll body constantly trying to get out but never succeeding and he's scary for his personality his dark sense of humor and creepy cackle + his shitty jokes and since he's a hacked robot I mean he could have a personality I could be wrong but even if he does it doesn't hold up as Brad Dourif and he's been voicing chucky since day 1 and has been doing this dolls voice for 30 years or more and Don Mancini the director of every child's play isn't directing it which won't help cause Don kept Chucky's charecter fresh never letting his charecter get old new jokes new plots and new kills in every movie and without Don or Brad the 2 people u depend on uh well oh. And what doesn't help is good guys being changed to buddi. I know it doesn't seem like it but if u go back along time ago in the 80s before child's play was out their was a doll named my buddy u might remember the doll if u think back but it had bright overalls and striped sleeves just like chucky and chucky was inspired by the doll but for copyright reasons they called the doll good guy which is pretty similar but even than my buddy was killed off cause of chucky. And it's been gone since the very first child's play movie and since it's the 200s now late 200s that doll has been forgotten by time and now they think they'll call it buddi which like still but cmon chucky already ruined Hasbro's huge hit toy back in the day give Hasbro a break. And chucky is known for being a tiny little pint sized asshole who gets away with tons of murders cause like I said just a normal doll with like 3 sentences but with the new ones technology it wouldn't let anybody pick him up cause he's protecting Andy which uh theirs nothing wrong with that but chucky is just a to himself person he only cares about himself and has no love for anyone but Tiffany and his kid Glenn/Glenda and even he's mean to his own wife he pretty much killed her in bride and he killed her in seed just saying he's a awful person and he will even go after his owner Andy to get his body. And after all he's done to Andy like get him put in a foster home pretty much kill everybody he loves make him get sent to a military school he destroyed Andy's childhood and theirs no forgiving for that. In the first 1 he hated chucky like 20 minutes into the movie after he killed aunt Maggie he hated chucky and tried to warn the adults but a course nobody would beleive a 6 year old kid who who's blaming murders on his beloved toy and Andy got blamed for the murders till his mom Karen found out the truth for herself and chucky escaped going on a killing spree through the city and well him being so smart with tons of technology it might be diffrent since Andy is older and he's 12 in this and his doll is full of technology it'd be easier to beleive chucky is responsible for the murders being a incredibly genius robot and even if they try to be like the first child's play and have tons of suspense till chucky finnaly reveals himself it won't be that scary cause we all no what's coming in the original child's play we were waiting till chucky would fully come out and he did like halfway through the movie putting chills down our spine as Karen starts realizing maybe Andy wasn't crazy after all and chucky really is alive and wants everybody dead so that's my long ass opinion on this child's play remake.

text: Ok I'm gonna give a theory, This new AI Chucky is designed to be the best friend of whoever it is programmed too, however the AI being not perfected becomes overly possesive and over protective of the child it's been programmed to be best freinds with. So, it kills anything it deems to be a threat to Andy at first, example school bullies. Over time however it will target anyone trying to separate it from Andy, it could explain why Chucky goes after the Mother, The Mother probably tries to take Chucky away from Andy after all the Murders. If they go in the direction of a murderous AI that will eliminate anyone that it deems to be a threat, then that will be a really intresting take on childs play, if Hal 9000 taught us anything is that Machines are the ultimate killer, they feel emotions, they feel no remorse, they cannot be reasoned with, only downside is that Chuckys personality would probably be underdeveloped since it's a machine not a human inside a doll.

text: I heard that someone at the company where the doll is made tampers with it to make it's learning abilities limitless. If's that's the came, that person's name should be Charles Lee Ray. Leaving him out completely would be criminal since Charles Lee Ray IS Chucky! Without Charles Lee Ray, there is no Chucky. There's just too much change to the mythology for to be a reboot of the Child's Play franchise. Leaving out Charles Lee Ray, the notorious Lakeshore Strangler responsible for a series of ritual voodoo killings, and replacing him with a corny robotic A.I. doll with attachment issues would be like remaking A Nightmare On Elm Street, but making it one of these suddenly trendy 80's throwbacks revolving around a bunch of pre-teens being given this new, cutting edge Ritalin type pill that's suppose to keep kids mellow, but  it's made from this exotic ancient plant that opens a gateways in the mind and Ooooo! dream demons come though instead of making it about a child murdering pedophile getting revenge on the people that burned him alive by taking their children... Just because it's 2019 doesn't mean everything has to be a CGI fest with a plot revolving around technology.

text: Let me preface this by saying I love Mark, he's an amazing voice actor and more importantly Luke freakin' Skywalker. Having said that he has some big shoes to fill. Brad has been the voice of Chucky for 7 movies spanning 31 years. While I'm sure he will do great, horror fans are very critical of change in the properties they love. Jackie Earle Haley did fine as Freddy but he wasn't really given a chance simply because he wasn't Robert Englund. Same with Derek Mears and Ken Kirzinger in the role of Jason because they weren't Kane Hodder. Now I'm not hating here, I'm just saying I definitely don't envy him. I'm a fan of Hamill and I hope he knocks it out of the park, and if anyone has a shot at it, he does. It kinda worked when Chucky was solo, and not many people knew about him, therefore element of surprise.   Physically, he shouldn't have the body strength and momentum to plunge knives into people, back then or now. At least not to the point that his victim is incapacitated, and can't fight back. People are able to grab and stop human stabbers. Child's Play 2 suggest that he's not endowed with strength and resilience above the average doll, especially in that scene where the factory machines tears him apart.

text: People please, only we can fight Hollywood on this rash of vomit inducing remakes. I know it's amazing that Mark Hamill is voicing Chucky, but is that reason alone enough to go see the damn thing? I think not. The movie's premise is stupid, the technology angle has been done to death and Chucky looks more like a Cabbage Patch doll with a glow up than a killer. If you go and see the movie just because of the voice actor for Chucky, then you're going to give Hollyweird the wrong impression; all they are going to see is $$$$ and keep pumping out reboots and remakes rather than original content. Please, I urge you to stay away from this and other rewhatevers and send a message to the movie producers! Rant over...

text: Child's Play (the original) is an odd duck, in that most people -- even those who were around at the time -- don't really remember (or never knew) that when it hit theaters, if you went, you knew you were watching a classic.  It was really such a fun time at the theater -- just a great, "fun" horror film with mass-appeal, and felt very much like an event.  It wasn't just another dumb horror movie -- it was special, and you knew it as you watched it.  It has such scares, but also has a great sense of humor -- not a horror/comedy, mind you, but ... "horror with heart?"  It really was something.  I approve of what I've seen from the remake so far.

text: I admit that in origin I was somewhat skeptical about this re-launch of the "Child's play", also because the saga of Don Mancini - the creator of Chucky - is still active and boasts seven chapters! Despite my skepticism, I went to the cinema and to my astonishment admit to having left the movie theater fully satisfied! The film is beautiful, well structured - in its simplicity of a horror film, this is obvious - and with an interesting and current reinvention; Examining the theme: (technology, use and abuse of everything that works with multiple wi.fi. connections) makes the film even more interesting and current, despite the unreality of the plot itself, but it is still a horror movie and we also like this! I became passionate about this film, so much so that - the next day - I returned to see it a second time, taking the invitation of some of my friends who still had to see it! However, although I really enjoyed the film, I have some small criticisms to raise; First of all, when you decide to reboot a brand and want to keep the same original title, it would be a good idea to insert a subtitle that distinguishes it from the official one (I suggest subtitles like: Rebirth 0 Reborn or Reborning 0 own Reboot)! Secondly, if you decide to make a reboot movie, you really need to diversify it to 100%! For example: the doll should not have been called Chucky (Buddy is more than good as a name); The child and his mother should have had different names (they didn't have to be the same characters in the original film) and maybe I would have called Chucky the very child himself! Andy and Karen Barclay could be the names of the policeman and his nice mom! Practically, to diversify the reboot and the original film in a more incisive way, but with quotations inserted in a different and apparently casual way; In this way, it would have worked even better, because it would have had a function similar to a "reboot - spin off" even if not official and canonical! The subtitle, perhaps, could have been "RE - IMMAGINING"! However, it is only my personal observation; I repeat, the film is beautiful (I've seen it twice) but with these little elements ones I would have preferred it even more! Anyway, good movie.

text: THIS MOVIE WAS HOT GARBAGE! From the very beginning of the movie you realize it.😑 1) This is a reboot. This has nothing to do with Charles Lee Ray and his story with Tiff. His arc is over. This Movie introduces us to a new form of the character with no background whatsoever. "Auday Dewey Demballah, GIVE THE POWER I BEG OF YOU!!" Yea...that's gone. 😂 Instead he's just a toy that "malfunctioned". He's jealous and wants The Kids to himself, he's naive like a child and kills some people. That's it.   2) The Kid cusses too much for my taste  I'm actually cool with a kid throwing a "damn" here or a "shit" there, but this movie tries too hard.🙄 3) Chucky walks around the fucking house and helps The Kid brush his damn teeth and packs his supplies for school??? Like Wtf??😧😲 *He should've just been his damn Dad* 🤦  4) THAT MOTHERFUCKING CGI!!!😤😡😠 They didn't use it ☝️ They didn't use it ✌️ They used it excessively!! My childhood has been tarnished. There's a few chuckles from time to time. But this trailer was MASSIVELY decieving.  PS *Fuck Orion* and Hollywood

text: this movie is a master piece, it's way better than the original and it completely makes up for those shitty sequels. this movie deserves sequels and here's why.   this movie doesn't do the whole killer gets killed and comes back for revenge cliche and you can appreciate it for being it's own film  just like thanos, this chucky doesn't just show how evil he is through out the film, there are some moments where he shows some heart which is rare for a villian; and if people doesn't like that, they should do with what they did with thanos in infinity war and endgame. show his pragmatic side in the first movie and then show his merciless more brutal side in the second movie  it makes a whole lot of sense why chucky is ugly and can hook up to the wifi, like furbies  the film uses very little cgi and they used a animatronic just like the original  the scene with the severed head wrapped in the present is both funny and intense at the same time  a worker disabling all of the safety protocols in a doll like that after getting fired by his boss is more realistic than all the voodoo stuff, besides, who keeps a voodoo doll of themselves
